N2  - Introduction: Over the last years, digital health tools have found their way into research and clinical trials in the field of multiple sclerosis (MS). While many healthcare professionals (HCPs) in the field agree that digital tools can standardize and improve MS care, adoption in the clinical routine has proven to be challenging. Objectives/Aims: Therefore, it is key to understand the value digital tools bring to care teams and the potential hurdles for the widespread adoption of these innovative solutions. Methods: We report on the clinical adoption of icompanion, a digital medical device solution that combines remote clinical monitoring with MRI insights. We share lessons learned and describe the efforts to improve patient retention, clinical visit efficiency, fit into clinical workflow, and data representation for care teams. In addition, we report insights from user interviews with HCPs and results from design validation tests for the novel icompanion HCP portal (including System Usability Scale). Results: icompanion is currently being used in 18 hospitals in 6 countries, and used by over 5700 people with MS. Average 3-month retention of patients (using icompanion without their care team) is 58%. Design validation for the novel HCP portal is underway and will be reported from 10-15 HCPs. The user interviews with 13 HCPs suggested that the most crucial factors for clinical adoption were (1) integration into electronic medical records (EMRs) (2) improving clinical visit efficiency (3) helping patients be better prepared for a visit (4) having an instant overview of clinical and MRI biomarkers from patients. Conclusion: Based on this data, the integration of digital health solutions in the clinical workflow (and EMR) is the most important driver for clinical adoption. Most HCPs see a clear value in access to remote monitoring data for patient management, but it is crucial that these solutions improve workflows as well.
