N2  - Introduction: Pain patients are increasingly asked to engage daily with smartphone applications and wearable devices for remote monitoring. However, some chronic pain patients are inconsistent with their patterns of wearable device use, charging, and responding to digital surveys. This clinical study examines whether patients will engage more regularly with these digital tools when provided with personalized feedback and targeted messaging regarding pain and common comorbidities via an entertaining user experience. Methods: This is a prospective, longitudinal, dual-arm clinical trial designed to enroll 28 patients into two study arms (14 patients per arm). In the traditional study arm, patients are provided with a remote monitoring smartphone application and wearable physiologic sensors. In the personalized experience study arm, patients are provided with these same tools, but are given a version of the remote monitoring app that provides a simple personalized user experience including engaging dialog, stories, targeted education related to chronic pain, and feedback on their health and holistic well-being. Patient engagement is measured by the consistency with which patients engage with the application, respond to therapy-related surveys, and use their wearable device properly. The interim analysis included in this report consists of the available survey data from five initial subjects in the traditional study arm before and during the SCS trial period. Enrollment of the first patient in the personalized experience arm occurred in July 2022 and follow-up and analysis are ongoing. Results: Three of five interviewed subjects wanted to be able to view their wearable data daily, while the other two subjects preferred to view them weekly. Subjects preferred using the Oura™ Ring and Apple Watch® due to their comfort and ease of use. Subjects also preferred the weekly recharging of the Oura ring (vs. daily watch charging). Conclusions: This research seeks to demonstrate feasibility for using patient-centric app design and artificial intelligence to improve user engagement with digital therapies in the field of chronic pain. We hypothesize that patients will be more engaged with use of digital tools if they are provided with an engaging and simple user experience that interests them and educates them regarding their chronic pain and related well-being topics. Chronic pain is a multi-dimensional disorder that can impact patient physical, social, and mental well-being [1]. Ongoing research should investigate whether digital education can also be used concurrently with neuromodulation to motivate patients to make positive lifestyle changes that are synergistic with their SCS therapy. Disclosure: Anne Christopher, MD: Abbott: Consulting Fee:, Biotronik: Fees for Non-CME/CE Services (e.g. advisor):, DERRON WILSON, MD: Abbott: Consulting Fee: Self, Abbott: Contracted Research: Self, Abbott: Speakers Bureau: Self, Boston Scientific: Speakers Bureau: Self, Boston Scientific: Contracted Research:, Biotronik: Consulting Fee:, JONATHAN HAGEDORN, MD: Abbott: Consulting Fee: Self, Boston Scientific: Consulting Fee: Self, Nevro: Consulting Fee: Self, Abbott: Contracted Research:, Saluda: Contracted Research:, Medtronic: Contracted Research:, Saluda: Consulting Fee:, Abbott: Consulting Fee:, Boston Scientific: Consulting Fee:, Nevro: Consulting Fee:, Saluda: Consulting Fee:, Abbott: Contracted Research:, Medtronic: Contracted Research:, Saluda: Contracted Research:, Nathan Miller: None, Jason Pope, MD: Abbott: Consulting Fee: Self, Vertiflex: Consulting Fee: Self, Saluda: Consulting Fee: Self, Vertos: Consulting Fee: Self, Thermaquil: Ownership Interest - Own Stocks: Self, SPR Therapeutics: Ownership Interest - Own Stocks: Self, Celeri Health: Ownership Interest - Own the Company: Self, Flowonix: Consulting Fee: Self, Stimgenics: Ownership Interest - Own Stocks: Self, Tersera: Consulting Fee: Self, GeneTech: Consulting Fee: Self, Neural Integ