N2  - Rationale: Recent advances in wearable sensor technologies have shown great potential in capturing real-life objective data at-home that can unlock great insights into clinical conditions change over time. Currently, there is no available wearable sensor to accurately capture pulmonary function remotely in the home, especially in children. 'Leo' is a novel Band-Aid sized wearable patch that uses impedance pneumography to measure respiratory parameters. The aim of this study was to evaluate the safety and performance of Leo compared to gold standard pneumotachography (PNT) in estimating respiratory rate, volume and flow. Methods: Twenty-six children with stable asthma ages 3-18 years were enrolled. The Leo device was placed over the mid-sternum. Participants breathed through a PNT device (Hans Rudolph, USA) to simultaneously capture respiratory rate, volume and flow while changing tidal volume in sitting, supine and lateral positions. Assessment duration was 10-15 minutes in each position and the measurements were also repeated 15 minutes after albuterol administration. The agreement between respiratory volume and flow waveform was assessed using standard error of the mean (SEM) and for respiratory rate using Pearson correlation coefficient. Participants completed a usability questionnaire. Results: Twenty two of the 26 recruited participants were included in the final respiratory analysis (mean age 10.2±4.3 years; 19 boys). Reasons for exclusion: excessive movement (2) and unable to adequately follow instructions (2). Respiratory rates median 19.7 (range 5-40) breaths/minute (bpm) and tidal volumes median 280 (range 100 - 3500) mL. The agreement of respiratory flow and volume was strong in all body postures and tidal volumes (mean ρ>0.95-0.85). The agreement between the PNT-derived and Leo-derived tidal volume estimates was also strong when Leo values were calibrated per subject and posture (r = 0.96, limits of agreement ± 0.2 Litres). Respiratory rates measured by Leo and PNT were highly correlated. (r = 0.98, limits of agreement ±1.5 breaths per minute). Twenty-two (85%) participants reported “very slight redness” at the skin site after Leo removal, and one reported “well-defined redness”. Otherwise, no other adverse events were reported. Participants reported a mean score of 3.6±0.63 (out of 5) for comfort (5 being very comfortable). Conclusions: These results suggest that Leo is a highly accurate and safe wearable sensor for respiratory monitoring in children with asthma. Further studies are needed to evaluate the clinical utility of Leo as a remote monitoring tool to assess pulmonary function.
